# Machine-Scannable Docs

- Treat `AGENTS.md` and `docs/catalog.json` as the canonical agent entry surfaces.
- Treat `README.md` and `docs/README.md` as human/editorial hubs.
- Treat `agent-manifest.json`, `llms.txt`, and `CLAUDE.md` as thin compatibility surfaces that should point back to the canonical files above.
- Keep `AGENTS.md` concise and pointer-oriented. Use `docs/catalog.json` for the machine-readable doc map instead of duplicating inventories in `AGENTS.md`.
- When adding or renaming canonical docs, update `docs/catalog.json` in the same pass. Update `docs/README.md`, `AGENTS.md`, and any affected compatibility surfaces when their routing or summary text changed.
- Durable docs under `docs/` should keep YAML frontmatter with at least `id`, `title`, `status`, `stage`, `type`, and `summary`.
- For core, milestone, and spec docs, also keep `authority`, `last_updated`, and `depends_on` current.
- Add `decision_refs` and `open_question_refs` when stable IDs materially constrain the doc.
- Prefer short scan-friendly sections near the top of canonical docs, such as `Purpose`, `Agent Quick Scan`, `Fast path`, `Use this doc when`, or `Not this doc for`.
- For agent entrypoint docs, keep stable sections for `Purpose`, `Use This File When`, `Not For`, `Update When`, and `Machine Contract`.
- Prefer stable IDs (`P*`, `D*`, `O*`, `M*`, `R*`) over copied prose when cross-referencing.
- Valid frontmatter must be real YAML, not markdown-styled pseudo-frontmatter.
- Keep contracts in flat lists, tables, JSON, or enumerated IDs. Do not bury critical constraints only in prose.
- When entrypoints or routing rules change, sync `docs/catalog.json`, `AGENTS.md`, relevant `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`, and any affected compatibility surfaces in the same pass.
- After routing-critical changes, run `bash scripts/validate-agent-docs.sh`.
- Keep curated research in `docs/research/`; preserve `research-output/` as frozen provenance.
